@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Concurrency Conflicts";
}

<section class="hero-card">
    <p class="eyebrow">40-Advanced-EFCore</p>
    <h2>Optimistic concurrency without mystery</h2>
    <p class="lead">
        This sample lets students trigger a real conflict, inspect the generated SQL, and practice a user-friendly resolution flow.
    </p>

    <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button-primary" asp-page="/Products/Index">Open Product List</a>
        <a class="button-secondary" asp-page="/Diagnostics/Index">Inspect SQL</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="grid-panels">
    <article class="panel">
        <h3>What Students Learn</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Why last-write-wins is risky.</li>
            <li>How EF Core uses a concurrency token in the `WHERE` clause.</li>
            <li>How to show database values and attempted values side by side.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
        <h3>Suggested Demo</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Open the same product in two browser tabs.</li>
            <li>Save tab A.</li>
            <li>Save tab B.</li>
            <li>Review the conflict and pick a resolution.</li>
        </ol>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
        <h3>What Goes Wrong</h3>
        <p>
            Both users start from the same original row version. The first save changes the record and increments the version.
            The second save still tries to update the older version, so EF Core refuses to overwrite the newer data silently.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
        <h3>Database Tooling</h3>
        <p>
            Use pgAdmin or Azure Data Studio to inspect the `Products` table while the app is running. Compare what you see there with the SQL shown on the diagnostics page.
        </p>
    </article>
</section>
